			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2013</a> poster:</span><br><i>Guided Grammar Convergence</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/VadimZaytsev.html">Vadim Zaytsev</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.48550/arXiv.1503.08476">10.48550/arXiv.1503.08476</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5b.html"><span class="tagM">T5B: Language Description Analysis</span></a><ul><li> The main contribution is analysis and reconciliation of language descriptions (grammars) via milestones of identity/equivalence and structural matching.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4b.html"><span class="tagL">T4B: Horizontal Transformation</span></a><ul><li> It aims to infer (bidirectional) transformation steps between different grammar representations, i.e., mappings/conversions across formalisms.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> The entire setting is about meta-languages for syntax/grammar specification (grammars “in a broad sense”), including normalization to a normal form.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3b.html"><span class="tagL">T3B: Transformation Languages</span></a><ul><li> Conventional and guided convergence are explicitly framed as sequences of grammar transformation steps (including automatically inferred ones).
</li></ul></li></ul>
